### Tested versions

- Reproducible in: v4.4.rc3.official [15ff45068], v4.4.dev7.official [46c8f8c5c]
- Not reproducible in: v4.4.dev6.official [1f47e4c4e]

### System information

Godot v4.4.rc3 - Windows 10 (build 19045) - Multi-window, 1 monitor - OpenGL 3 (Compatibility) - NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1050 Ti (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.7260) - Intel(R) Core(TM) i3-10105 CPU @ 3.70GHz (8 threads)

### Issue description

Godot reports a varying is not being used, while it is being used.

### Steps to reproduce

Create or open a shader with a varying and look for warning in the bottom of the shader editor.

Found and reproduced with this shader (included in the MRP below):

```
shader_type canvas_item;

uniform float level;

varying vec4 vertex_color;

void vertex() {
	vertex_color = COLOR;
}

void fragment()
{
	COLOR = vertex_color;
	COLOR.a *= level;
}
```

Here Godot claims `vertex_color` is not being used: `Line 5 (UNUSED_VARYING):The varying 'vertex_color' is declared but never used.`

Note: The shader is based on an example from the documentation at [COLOR and TEXTURE](https://docs.godotengine.org/en/stable/tutorials/shaders/shader_reference/canvas_item_shader.html#color-and-texture):

```
varying vec4 vertex_color;
void vertex() {
  vertex_color = COLOR;
}
void fragment() {
  COLOR = vertex_color;
}
```


### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[svwt.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19036041/svwt.zip)

### Tested versions

- Tested with 4.3 stable

### System information

Godot v4.3.stable.mono - Windows 10.0.19045 - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3080 Ti (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.6636) - AMD Ryzen 9 5950X 16-Core Processor (32 Threads)

### Issue description

When a child class overrides a partner's property the Editor's Inspector will show the property under both the parent's class sub-category along with the child's.

The overriding property will also show the parent's value and not the child's value.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a3216e1b-e6a5-4228-9c7b-71ac242ba984)
Expect `Test Array` to be of size 2 and for `Test Int` to have a value of 2.

I would also expect `Test Array` and `Test Int` to show only once under the lowest level child class that they are overridden in. In my example project this would be Test2.

<br/>
<br/>

Here is a quick Edit in paint of how I would expect it to look:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/412150b6-9c5a-444e-b58b-c276f83d0989)


<br/>
<br/>
<br/>


Further, If I created another class Test3 that extends Test2 and only overrides `Test Int` with a value of 3, then I would expect the Inspector to show `Test Array` with a size of 2 under Test2 and `Test Int` to show with a value of 3 under Test3. The Test subcategory would be empty.

### Steps to reproduce

```
using Godot;
using System;

namespace ANameSpace {
    public partial class Test : Node3D {
        [Export] public virtual int[] TestArray { get; set; } = new int[1];

        [Export] public virtual int TestInt { get; set; } = 1;

        public override void _Ready() {
            GD.Print($"\n\nTestArray Length : {TestArray.Length}\nTestInt: {TestInt}");
        }
    } 
}
```
```
using Godot;
using System;

namespace ANameSpace {
    public partial class Test2 : Test {
        [Export] public override int[] TestArray { get; set; } = new int[2];

        [Export] public override int TestInt { get; set; } = 2;

    } 
}
```

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[simple.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19003180/simple.zip)
